        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi> | (<hi rend="print">Railway Station | Orpington. S.E.R.</hi>)</placeName>
                    <date>November 8<hi rend="superscript">th</hi> 1881</date>
                    <salute>My dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
                    <p>I noticed your account of the pipes in the under-clay, but feel quite unable to express any opinion on the subject.<ref target="#foot.f1"/> It is certain that roots often run down worm-burrow, but I believe that roots can penetrate the ground to a great depth without such aid. I am much pleased that my book has at all interested you;<ref target="#foot.f2"/> it has been a complete surprise to me how many persons have cared for the subject.—</p>
                    <p>I remain, my dear Sir | Yours faithfully | Ch. Darwin</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">0.1 (<hi rend="italic">Railway … S.E.R.</hi>)] <hi rend="italic">parentheses added</hi></note>
                <note xml:id="tnote.n2">1.3 roots] <hi rend="italic">above del</hi> ‘they’</note>
            </div>
        </div>
        
        
        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-13465.xml">letter from T. M. Reade, 6 November 1881</ref>. Reade had found deep roots in clay, some of which were lined with mould, and wondered whether the roots had followed the path of worm burrows.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_2241.xml"><hi rend="italic">Earthworms</hi></ref>.</note>
            
            
        </div>
    
